The most interesting thing I liked about the dataframe, it has got a lot of columns! And you can take any of them as center of interest! And now I have interested in CreditGrade and ProsperScore columns.

CreditGrade column has grading for loans before 2009

  • AA, A, B are good grades
  • C, D are moderate grades
  • E, HR or NC are low grades

ProsperScore column has grading for loans after 2009

  • grading includes numbers from 1 to 11, they mean low to high grades respectively

So, let's see which grades for loans are most often!

Conclusion¶

Ok, guys! Today we have done some insights to Prosper Loan data and try to answer the questions that we interested. I think we have done a good job! Do you remember the question we interested? If yes, help me to make conclusions. So, let's start.

According to the visualisations that we made, we can say following facts about the data.

  • the most common loan amounts are 5k, 10k, and 15k dollars in the dataframe.
  • the most common investment for each investor is between 30 and 100 dollars.
  • the most common credit grades are moderate grades.
  • your credit grade score depends on income range, the higher income leads to higher credit grade.
  • in 2013 the prosper loans likely to be most common among users.
  • the most common ivestment case we have seen is for lower amount of money and lower investors count.
  • the people with higher credit score, get loan in a range between 5000 and 15000 dollars.
  • more investors invest money to the loans with higher credit score.
  • the most common loan term 3 years.
  • it is likely that the people with middle income uses prosper loans
  • lower APR leads to higher loan amount
  • the loans with higher credit grade leads to lower APR

I think that's all for know. If you find further question to investigate, good luck with that!
